Poverty is a near universal condition in much of the world.
One billion people live on less than one dollar a day.
More than 110 million Third World children lack access even to primary education.
In Mexico, life expectancy for the poorest 10 percent is 20 years less than for the richest 10 percent.
In 1992, World Bank president Lewis Preston issued a directive to link loan volume to the strength of a country's efforts to fight poverty.
The link between loans and poverty relief forms part of a new drive to make poverty alleviation the bank's central mission in the 1990's.
In 1990, Third World debtors had to pay $50.1 billion more to service their debts to the United and other creditors than they received in new loans.
Until 1984, the richer countries had provided more in new loans to Third World nation than those countries paid back.
In September 1991, John Hatch, founder of the non-profit Foundation for International Community Assistance developed a concept of using small revolving loans to poor women to finance their private enterprise.
Using the Hatch concept, U.S. development organizations are finding that some of the world's poorest entrepreneurs repay their debts at rates approaching 100%.